[R8] {'_type': 'review', 'review_id': 'UR3j0X6i8jJzlPgHMsFPAw', 'user_id': 'Ie02V8osbBJo7kuhYfi5zg', 'business_id': '_C7QiQQc47AOEv4PE3Kong', 'stars': 3.0, 'useful': 0, 'funny': 0, 'cool': 0, 'text': "While visiting New Orleans, my husband and I recently had our wedding anniversary dinner at Commander's Palace, which came highly recommended by friends. While the food was delicious (as expected), what was not expected was the service. 
Our experience started by being brought to the bar (through the active kitchen which was cool) while we waited for our table to be ready. When we were sat at the table, our waiter (Dwayne) immediately greets us, removing our napkins from our plates to return to my lap but never to my husbands. We ordered some apps and our meal and a pour of Pappy (we were impressed at the availability and range of Pappy). Upon receiving our drinks, something seemed to change with our server, Dwayne. He seemed to be annoyed by our presence and disengaged with providing the service that had be raved about. My husband and I are still unsure what we could've done to warrant a change in demeanor. While we barely got the occasional check in, 2 nearby tables were doted on. My husband never got his napkin (that he asked for back) and we were never given the opportunity to ask for another drink. By the time we finished dinner, we were eager to leave. Given it was our anniversary and that my husband notified the restaurant upon booking, we were given ice cream (sweet policy of the restaurant) that was pretty much dropped at our table. At this point, my husband and I felt that we were stuck waiting to leave and most certainly weren't going to upset Dwayne by not having the ice cream. We couldn't have signed that bill fast enough. 
